Support Vector Machine Exercise

(This text is google translated from Japanese original text.)
Let's facilitate our understanding the support vector machine through exercise.
目次

Prepare iris data

Prepare the data. I will use the iris data again this time.
load fisheriris;

construct a linear SVM for setosa and versicolor

Prepare petal data

The typical support vector machine is a binary classifier.
First, let's try using only the data of setosa and versicolor .
To visualize, petals ( Petal) I will try using only the data of the length and width of.
(Of course, you can use PCA to make it two- dimensional, but I thought that it would be difficult to understand, so I will use petals for the time being.)
indices = 1:100;
X = meas(indices, 3:4);
Y = species(indices);

Observe the data

First, let's plot only the petals of the iris data. Yeah, it was such data.
The setosa was relatively far from the other two .
gscatter(X(:,1), X(:,2), Y, 'rg');
xlabel('Petal length')
ylabel('Petal width')

Construct a linear SVM

Let's use a linear SVM . You can build it with the following command.
By default, the parameter that governs the soft margin is set as .
I don't know how to build a discriminator with full hard margin in MATLAB , so let's try with , to make it perform as close as the hard margin.
SVMModel = fitcsvm(X,Y, "BoxConstraint", 100);
Once you have built a discriminator, let's check how to use it.
doc SVMModel
You can see the documentation for the class corresponding to this object by executing the command above.
According to the documentation, the SVMModel object seems to be an object of the ClassificationSVM class.
In the command line, live editor, etc., add a dot after " SVMModel " and press the TAB key repeatedly to complete the method or property.
predict is a function that identifies new data.

Check parameters learned by linear SVM

Let's check the learned parameters for a moment.
SVMModel.Beta
ans = 2×1
1.2941 0.8235
SVMModel.Bias
ans = -3.7882
Let's find Beta and Bias as β and b respectively, the given identification function is expressed as follows.
Now, the vector of β is directing to the upper right in the feature space, so the discriminant function becomes larger toward the upper right.
It is a good idea to try to figure out what kind of shape of by hand.
After solving, let's go back to the plot of petal data drawn with gscatter and check if the line is reasonable.

Visualize results learned by linear SVM

It's a bit confusing, but try typing the following code and running it.
You can see the contents of a variable by clicking on the variable in the workspace.
If it is a live editor, execute it once and display the contents by moving the mouse cursor.
svInd = SVMModel.IsSupportVector;
h = 0.1; % Mesh grid step size
[X1,X2] = meshgrid(min(X(:,1)):h:max(X(:,1)), min(X(:,2)):h:max(X(:,2))); % calculate grid points
[~,score] = SVMModel.predict([X1(:),X2(:)]); % calculate scores at the each grid point
scoreGrid = reshape(score(:,2),size(X1,1),size(X2,2));
figure
gscatter(X(:,1), X(:,2), Y, 'rg');
hold on
plot(X(svInd,1),X(svInd,2),'ko','MarkerSize',10, "LineWidth",1) % Mark support vectors
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid); % draw contour
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [0 0],'k', "LineWidth", 1); %draw decision bounday
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [1 1],'k'); %draw f(x)=1
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [-1 -1],'k'); %draw f(x)=-1
colorbar;
xlabel('Petal length')
ylabel('Petal width')
legend(["setosa", "versicolor", "support vectors", "contour", "decision boundary($f(x)=0$)", "$f(x)=1$", "$f(x)=-1$"], "Interpreter", "latex");
hold off
When you see a picture like this, it gives you an image.
The decision plane (decision boundary) is at .
The support vector is at .
the section of between and is the so-called no-entry area.

Build SVM for classifying versicolor and virginica

Prepare petal data

Now let's try using only versicolor and virginica .
Just like petals ( Petal) we will try using only the data of the length and width of.
indices = 51:150;
X = meas(indices, 3:4);
Y = species(indices);

Observe the data

Plot in the same way as before.
That's right, it was a bit overlaid.
gscatter(X(:,1), X(:,2), Y, 'gb');

Apply linear SVM

It doesn't look like a straight line to separate completely, but I dare to use a linear SVM .
You can see the behavior of the soft margin.
It's actually better to make it a function without writing the same code, but let's not worry about it.
SVMModel = fitcsvm(X,Y, "BoxConstraint", 1);
svInd = SVMModel.IsSupportVector;
h = 0.1; % Mesh grid step size
[X1,X2] = meshgrid(min(X(:,1)):h:max(X(:,1)), min(X(:,2)):h:max(X(:,2))); % calculate grid points
[~,score] = SVMModel.predict([X1(:),X2(:)]); % calculate scores at the each grid point
scoreGrid = reshape(score(:,2),size(X1,1),size(X2,2));
figure
gscatter(X(:,1), X(:,2), Y, 'rg');
hold on
plot(X(svInd,1),X(svInd,2),'ko','MarkerSize',10, "LineWidth",1) % Mark support vectors
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid); % draw contour
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [0 0],'k', "LineWidth", 1); %draw decision bounday
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [1 1],'k'); %draw f(x)=1
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [-1 -1],'k'); %draw f(x)=-1
colorbar;
xlabel('Petal length')
ylabel('Petal width')
legend(["versicolor", "virginica", "support vectors", "contour", "decision boundary($f(x)=0$)", "$f(x)=1$", "$f(x)=-1$"], "Interpreter","latex");
hold off
For each of the red and green, the data that did not separate correctly came out. Also, it seems that the number of support vectors has increased.
Originally, when the hard margin was used, the function was adjusted for the support vectors .
If you allow the soft margin, data will also enter the prohibited area. Furthermore, some data remains in the area on the other side.
These too will influence the formation of the decision plane.
(Theoretically, these are treated as support vectors because they use slack variables to satisfy the equality constraints of SVM optimization problems.)
では、 C をもう少し大きくして同じことをやってみましょう。
SVMModel = fitcsvm(X,Y, "BoxConstraint", 1000);
svInd = SVMModel.IsSupportVector;
h = 0.1; % Mesh grid step size
[X1,X2] = meshgrid(min(X(:,1)):h:max(X(:,1)), min(X(:,2)):h:max(X(:,2))); % calculate grid points

figure

hold on
plot(X(svInd,1),X(svInd,2),'ko','MarkerSize',10, "LineWidth",1) % Mark support vectors
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid); % draw contour
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [0 0],'k', "LineWidth", 1); %draw decision bounday
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [1 1],'k'); %draw f(x)=1
contour(X1,X2,scoreGrid, [-1 -1],'k'); %draw f(x)=-1
colorbar;
xlabel('Petal length')
ylabel('Petal width')
legend(["versicolor", "virginica", "support vectors", "contour", "decision boundary($f(x)=0$)", "$f(x)=1$", "$f(x)=-1$"], "Interpreter","latex");
hold off
It seems that the circled support vectors have decreased considerably.
The number of data and violation distance that have gone to the prohibited area and the other side are short.。

Apply Gaussian SVM with optimization

variously waving, it can also be optimized. There is a method called grid search that is often used as a method to try these from the edge.
Let's try.
SVMModel = fitcsvm(X, Y, "KernelFunction", "gaussian", ...
'OptimizeHyperparameters','auto',...
'HyperparameterOptimizationOptions',struct('AcquisitionFunctionName',...
'expected-improvement-plus', "Optimizer", "gridsearch"));

Build SVM for all kinds of data

Prepare petal data

Let' use all data in the dataset.
indices = 1:150;
X = meas(indices, 3:4);
Y = species(indices);

Observe the data

gscatter(X(:,1), X(:,2), Y, 'rgb');
xlabel('Petal length')
ylabel('Petal width')

Build and visualize linear SVM

The FitPosterior option will be used only for further visualization.
SVMModel = fitcecoc(X, Y, 'FitPosterior',true);
The area is colored and classified into three classes as follows.
SVMModel.predict(X(1,:));
gscatter(X(:,1), X(:,2), Y, 'rgb');
hold on;
h=0.1;
[X1,X2] = meshgrid(min(X(:,1)):h:max(X(:,1)), min(X(:,2)):h:max(X(:,2)));
[~,~,~, posteriors] = SVMModel.predict([X1(:), X2(:)]); % calculate scores at the each grid point
scatter(X1(:), X2(:) , 20, posteriors, "filled", "MarkerFaceAlpha", 0.2);
xlabel('Petal length')
ylabel('Petal width')
hold off;

Summary

In this text, I constructed and visualized various classifiers using SVM for iris data .
A practical guide to SVM classification provides detailed explanations using specific examples using the software libsvm as a tool .
A lot of know-how to use SVM well is written. Please take a look and try it.
